  "text": "This audit identified five critical TLS/SSL implementation files in Firefox's Network Security Services (NSS) library under security/nss/lib/ssl/:\n\n1. **ssl3con.c** (517KB, 517,196 bytes): The primary file implementing SSL 3.0 and TLS 1.2 record processing and cipher suite negotiation. Key functions include ssl3_GenerateRSAPMS (RSA pre-master secret generation), ssl3_ComputeMasterSecret (master secret computation from pre-master secret), and ssl3_DeriveConnectionKeys (deriving record layer encryption and MAC keys). This file also handles handshake message processing including ClientHello, ServerHello, Certificate, CertificateRequest, ServerKeyExchange, and Finished messages. The file manages cipher suite configuration and negotiation with the ssl3CipherSuiteCfg array and implements record layer operations with ssl3_BuildRecordPseudoHeader and ssl3_ComputeRecordMAC.\n\n2. **tls13con.c** (259KB, 258,885 bytes): Implements TLS 1.3 handshake and record processing with modern cryptographic operations. Key functions include tls13_SetCipherSpec (installing cipher specs with epoch-based record number separation), tls13_DeriveSecret (using HKDF-based key derivation), and tls13_HandleServerKeyShare (processing server key share extensions). The file handles the TLS 1.3 simplified handshake flow including ClientHello, ServerHello, EncryptedExtensions, Certificate, CertificateVerify, and Finished messages, plus session ticket handling and early data (0-RTT) processing.\n\n3. **dtlscon.c** (48KB, 47,810 bytes): Implements DTLS (Datagram TLS) protocol-specific handling for unreliable transport. Key functions include dtls_TLSVersionToDTLSVersion and dtls_DTLSVersionToTLSVersion (protocol version mapping between TLS and DTLS wire formats), dtls_HandleHandshake (processing fragmented handshake messages), and dtls_FragmentHandshake (fragmenting outgoing handshake messages for MTU constraints). The file also implements retransmission timers, message flight transmission, and out-of-order message handling necessary for unreliable UDP transport.\n\n4. **ssl3ecc.c** (32KB, 32,137 bytes): Implements Elliptic Curve Cryptography (ECC) operations for ECDHE and ECDSA cipher suites. Key functions include ssl_NamedGroup2ECParams (converting named groups to SEC_ASN1_OBJECT_ID encoded EC parameters), ssl_ECPubKey2NamedGroup (extracting named groups from EC public keys), ssl_CreateECDHEPrivateKey (generating ephemeral ECDHE keys), and ssl_CreateECDHEphemeralKeyPair (creating full key pairs for ECDHE). The file handles all ECC-related cryptographic operations including parameter validation and key agreement.\n\n5. **sslexp.h** (57KB, 56,875 bytes): Header file declaring experimental SSL/TLS APIs designed to remain unstable across NSS versions. Key declarations include SSL_GetExperimentalAPI (macro for accessing experimental functions), SSL_EXPERIMENTAL_API (macro framework for calling experimental functions safely), SSL_GetExtensionSupport (querying extension support levels), and SSL_InstallExtensionHooks (registering custom extension writers and handlers). The file provides a controlled interface for applications to safely use non-stable APIs and implement custom TLS extensions.\n\nAll files are located in the mozilla-firefox/firefox repository at security/nss/lib/ssl/. These files collectively implement the complete TLS protocol stack (SSL 3.0, TLS 1.0-1.3, DTLS) with support for both traditional and modern cipher suites, ECC operations, and extensible experimental APIs."
